,"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the predominant immunoglobulin in mucosal secretions. In its secretory form, IgA exists as a dimer and provides protection by preventing pathogen adhesion to mucosal surfaces while neutralising toxins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgG\u003C/strong\u003E is the most abundant antibody in blood, providing systemic immunity through opsonisation, complement activation, and neutralisation of pathogens. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgM\u003C/strong\u003E is produced early in the primary immune response and excels at activating the complement system. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgD\u003C/strong\u003E serves mainly as an antigen receptor on naive B cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgE\u003C/strong\u003E mediates allergic responses and provides protection against parasitic infections by activating mast cells and eosinophils. Secretory IgA is particularly important as it can withstand the harsh conditions at mucosal surfaces and provides the first line of defence against pathogens at these sites.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Immunoglobulin A (IgA) is the primary antibody responsible for mucosal immunity.","IgA exists in both monomeric form in blood and dimeric secretory form at mucosal surfaces.","Secretory IgA prevents pathogen adhesion to mucosal surfaces and neutralises toxins."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Justiz Vaillant AA, Jamal Z, Patel P, et al. Immunoglobulin. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513460/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97431"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions",